Difference between chmod and chown?
Better Answer

chmod is used to modify file or directory permissions such as Read, Write, and Execute permissions.

chown is used to change the ownership of a file or directory by assigning it to a different user or group.

Example
chmod
chmod 755 file.txt

Result:

rwxr-xr-x

Changes permissions.

chown
chown sandhya file.txt

Changes owner from one user to another.

Project-Based Answer

During Linux user provisioning, I used chmod to assign appropriate file and directory permissions and chown to set the correct ownership for users, groups, and home directories.

One-Line Interview Answer

chmod changes permissions, whereas chown changes ownership.
